{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491057","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491057"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:30:47+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:30:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"820"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"820","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/820"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.73,0.04,0.06,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"820"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81703"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"820","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/820"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"820"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67002"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"181"},{"type":"tags","id":"582"},{"type":"tags","id":"738"},{"type":"tags","id":"1137"},{"type":"tags","id":"3399"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"9278"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3861"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3883"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81703","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/81703"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with four episodes of vomiting bright red blood within the past hour. He reports several months of anorexia, fatigue, and 6 kg of unintentional weight loss. He has no significant medical history but drinks five to 10 standard alcoholic drinks daily for over 20 years. He does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell and malnourished. His pulse rate is 120/min, blood pressure 100/60 mmHg, dropping to 85/40 mmHg on sitting up. His abdomen is moderately distended with shifting dullness and generalised tenderness without peritonism. His spleen is palpable well below the left costal margin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInitial blood results show:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin: 65 g/L (135-175)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite cell count: 13 x 10^9/L (4-11)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of the haematemesis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Mallory-Weiss tear","Oesophageal varices","Alcoholic gastritis","Boerhaave syndrome","Gastric lymphoma"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features of decompensated cirrhosis including ascites, splenomegaly, and malnutrition in the context of significant alcohol use. The elevated white cell count likely represents a stress response to acute blood loss and possible concurrent infection. \u003Cstrong\u003EOesophageal varices\u003C/strong\u003E are the most likely cause of upper gastrointestinal bleeding in patients with cirrhosis, responsible for 60-65% of cases. Portal hypertension from cirrhosis leads to the formation of varices at sites of porto-systemic anastomosis, including the lower oesophagus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMallory-Weiss tears\u003C/strong\u003E typically present with haematemesis after a history of forceful vomiting, which is not present here. These mucosal tears usually cause smaller volume bleeding than seen in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlcoholic gastritis\u003C/strong\u003E, while common in heavy alcohol users, typically presents with epigastric pain and smaller volume bleeding. The presence of portal hypertension features makes varices more likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBoerhaave syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E (oesophageal rupture) presents with severe chest or abdominal pain after forceful vomiting, often with subcutaneous emphysema. Significant haematemesis is not typical.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGastric lymphoma\u003C/strong\u003E is a rare cause of upper gastrointestinal bleeding. While it can cause splenomegaly, the acute presentation with haemodynamic compromise in a patient with clear evidence of portal hypertension makes varices much more likely.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Oesophageal varices are the most common cause of upper gastrointestinal bleeding in patients with cirrhosis, responsible for 60-65% of cases.","Clinical features of portal hypertension include splenomegaly, ascites, and varices at sites of porto-systemic anastomosis.","Signs of decompensated cirrhosis include ascites, muscle wasting, and unintentional weight loss."],"references":["Wilkins T, Wheeler B, Carpenter M. Upper Gastrointestinal Bleeding in Adults: Evaluation and Management. Am Fam Physician. 2020 Mar 1;101(5):294-300. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32109037/","Kovacs TOG, Jensen DM. Varices: Esophageal, Gastric, and Rectal. Clin Liver Dis. 2019 Nov;23(4):625-642. PMID: 31563215. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31563215/","Gunarathne et al. Cirrhotic portal hypertension: From pathophysiology to novel therapeutics. World J Gastroenterol. 2020 Oct 28;26(40):6111-6140. PMCID: PMC7596642. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33177789/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67002"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"820"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67002","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/67002"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-26T20:06:53+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-26T20:06:53+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"820"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81703"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":